Casuarina littoralis

   [4344.jpg]
    Authority   Salisb
      Family    Magnoliopsida:Hamamelidae:Casuarinales:Casuarinaceae
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 4344

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION It is usually a large shrub or a small tree reaching
   a height of 3-12 m. USES The wood is used as fuel and charcoal, tunery,
   rough furniture and farmhouse construction. The tree can provide wind
   and soil protection and it can be used as an ornamental. GROWING PERIOD
   Perennial. COMMON NAMES Black sheoak, Black oak, Bull oak. FURTHER INF
   Scientific synonym: Allocasuarina littoralis. Black sheoak is native of
   eastern Australia, with a main distribution between latitudes 10-43Â°S.
   It can be found at elevations between sea level and 1500 m. It occurs
   on a variety of sites from lowland flats to undulating country and
   mountain peaks. It has the potential to become a weed.

   Sources
   SOURCES (Casuarina littoralis Salisb.)
   National RC 1984 pp 82-83 [KTMP, DRA, SAL, LIG, USE, TEMP, RAIN, FER,
   TEXT]
   Turnbull J 1986 pp 226-227 [TEMP, KTMP, RAIN, TEXT, PH, FER, USE]

